Abstract:
While teaching a course on integral equations, I noticed that a straight-
forward combination of Neumann series and Fourier series for the resolvent
(or the solution) of an integral equation has good approximation qualities.
This short article presents and investigates this combination of approxi-
mating series.

The obvious practical advantage is that convergence of the Fourier series im-
proves with increased m. The resolvent can be eﬀectively approximated by a
few terms of the Neumann series plus several terms of Fourier series. Even if λ
is near some large eigenvalue λn, the terms with |λk| > |λn| diminish quickly.
From the probed literature it appears that the closest topic that may suggest
formulas (11), (12) is “acceleration of convergence of Fourier series” or “over-
coming the Gibbs phenomenon” by means of polynomial subtraction [Adc11,
§5.1], [Ner19]. The Neumann series part in (12) is often polynomial, as the ex-
ample of the following section illustrates. The term “Fourier-Neumann series”
has been used to refer to Fourier series in terms of Bessel functions [CV09].

The poles of these solutions at the eigenvalues λ are well captured by the re-
spective Fourier terms. With those Fourier terms, the approximation error can
be seen as a continuous function of λ.
With explicit solutions at hand, we may analyze approximation quality of
diﬀerently truncated mixed Neumann-Fourier series (18), (26)–(28). Figure 1
and Table 1 represent a batch of relevant data. Figure 1 demonstrates how
adding just one Neumann series term diminishes the approximation error by a
factor ≈ 100. The approximation error is largest at the endpoint x = 1, because
the non-homogeneous term f(x) = x in (13) does not satisfy the boundary
condition (15) at x = 1, resulting in a weak version of the Gibbs phenomenon
[Adc11, §4.2]. Table 1 suggests that adding a Neumann series term is more
worthwhile than adding a Fourier term, unless λ becomes large while the number
of Fourier terms lags the number of Neumann terms. The approximation errors
for negative λ are of the same order as respectively those for |λ|.
